Exercise 1)

The Telco Customer Churn prediction task is a classification and supervised learning problem.

  • This is a classification problem because the goal is to predict whether a customer will churn (leave the service) or not, which is a binary outcome.

  • This is a supervised learning problem because we are provided with labeled data (the target variable is whether the customer churned or not), so it is a supervised learning task.

Exercise 3)

churn_counts <- table(telco_data$Churn)
barplot(churn_counts, 
        main = "Churn vs No Churn", 
        xlab = "Churn", 
        ylab = "Frequency", 
        col = c("skyblue", "orange"))
churn_counts

  No  Yes 
5163 1869

The churn counts show that there are 5163 customers who did not churn (No) and 1869 customers who churned (Yes). No churn (5163) is significantly higher then Yes churn (1869), which indicates that the data set is imbalanced.

What this implies for modeling:

  • Model Bias Towards Majority Class: With most customers classified as âNoâ, the model may lean towards predicting the majority class more often, which can overlook the minority (churners).

  • Poor Recall in Minority Class: Imbalance can lead to poor recall for the minority class (âYesâ), meaning the model may not correctly identify all the customers who are likely to churn.

  • Misleading Accuracy: Model may have a misleading accuracy due to the imbalance. i.e.Â if the model predicts âNoâ churn for every case, it could still achieve ~73% accuracy just by predicting the majority class, failing to identify actual churners.

  geom_bar(position = "fill") +
  labs(title = "Churn Rate by Gender", y = "Proportion", x = "Gender") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("No" = "blue", "Yes" = "red"))
